Hi Friends,

This week I wanted to share my thoughts on the Kendrick and Drake beef, some of the backstory leading up to it and the overall fallout. Ever since Kendrick released his "Like That" verse the world has been on fire with talk about how each rapper mentioned would respond. J.Cole and Drake definitely took different routes and hip hop has been the talk of pop culture since the back and forth started. 

Way more people have had problems with Drake since his career started than most know. He's actually been in conflicts with Common, Pharrell, and Diddy. Some have come back up in this beef with Kendrick but new ones have popped up like with Rick Ross, The Weeknd, Asap Rocky, Metro Boomin, Future, and Kanye. 

If everyone you've ever worked with or looked up to eventually hates you you have to wonder if you're not the problem. Kendrick has released 4 diss tracks that span old school hip hop, funk, jazz, and an eclectic mix of beats. No matter who you were rooting for going in to this there is no doubt that fans have walked away with a different impression of both rappers. 

Thanks for watching. If you enjoy please share with someone who could use a laugh and most of all thanks for being my friends.

Recipe:
To make zebra cakes, start by whisking ¬æ cup cake flour, ¬º teaspoon baking powder, ‚Öõ teaspoon baking soda, and ¬æ teaspoon kosher salt in a medium bowl. In a separate bowl, beat 3 egg yolks and ¬º cup sugar with a hand mixer until ribbony, then stream in ¬º cup neutral oil, ¬º cup buttermilk, and a teaspoon of vanilla extract. Pour the yolk mixture into the flour mixture and whisk until smooth. In a separate bowl, combine three egg whites, ¬º cup sugar, and a pinch of cream of tartar and beat with an electric mixer to stiff peaks. Fold the whites into the batter, then scrape onto a parchment-lined half sheet tray. Bake in a 225-degree oven until springy to the touch and golden, then let cool. Trim the edges then cut the sponge into 6-cm-wide strips and trim them horizontally so they‚Äôre about 7mm thick. Freeze the pieces. 

To make the filling, combine 3 ounces egg whites, 5.5 ounces of sugar, ¬Ω teaspoon kosher salt, and a pinch of cream of tartar in the bowl of a stand mixer set over a double boiler and stir until the sugar dissolves. Whip the egg whites until firm peaks form and the meringue is room temperature, then gradually beat in 10 ounces of room temperature butter. Scrape down the sides of the bowl and beat in 1 tablespoon of vanilla paste. Pipe a layer of buttercream onto the surfaces of the cake strips using a basketweave tip, then sandwich the cake together. Chill briefly, then cut out hexagons using a serrated knife and template. Chill the cakes. 

In a large bowl, whisk together 4 cups powdered sugar, ¬º cup hot water, ¬º cup light corn syrup, and 1 teaspoon vanilla extract until smooth. Whisk in 142g melted white chocolate, then thin with more hot water to the desired consistency. Place over a saucepan of hot water to keep warm. Spread a thin layer over the tops of the cakes, let set at room temperature, then place the cakes one at a time glaze-size down on a large fork and spoon the glaze over the cakes until fully enrobed. Place on a wire rack and let set. Pipe thin lines of melted chocolate over the surfaces of the cakes in a wavy pattern and let set.
